{
  "children":[
    {"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Core Meaning & Usage"}],"depth":2,"type":"heading"},
    {"children":[{"type":"text","value":"争 represents "},{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"active competition or contention for desired outcomes"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":". It's used for:"}],"type":"paragraph"},
    {"children":[{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Competition"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":": 争第一 (zhēng dì yī) - \"compete for first place\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Arguments"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":": 争吵 (zhēngchǎo) - \"quarrel/argue\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Striving"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":": 争取 (zhēngqǔ) - \"strive for/fight for\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Disputes"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":": 争议 (zhēngyì) - \"controversy/dispute\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"}],"ordered":true,"spread":false,"start":1,"type":"list"},
    {"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Examples"}],"depth":2,"type":"heading"},
    {"children":[{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"争夺"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":" (zhēngduó) - \"compete for/contend for\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"争论"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":" (zhēnglùn) - \"debate/argue\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"争气"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":" (zhēngqì) - \"try to make a good showing\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"不争"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":" (bù zhēng) - \"not compete/avoid conflict\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"},{"checked":null,"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"type":"text","value":"争先恐后"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","value":" (zhēng xiān kǒng hòu) - \"strive to be first and fear to lag behind\""}],"type":"paragraph"}],"spread":false,"type":"listItem"}],"ordered":false,"spread":false,"start":null,"type":"list"},
    {"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Cultural Context"}],"depth":2,"type":"heading"},
    {"children":[{"type":"text","value":"争 reflects the complex Chinese attitude toward competition, which balances individual striving with\nsocial harmony. While competition (争) is seen as natural and sometimes necessary for progress,\nexcessive争 (fighting/arguing) is discouraged in favor of cooperation. The ideal is \"争气不争利\"\n(zhēngqì bù zhēnglì) - \"strive for honor, not profit.\" Traditional Chinese philosophy emphasizes\nthat the highest form of competition is self-improvement rather than defeating others, embodying the\nprinciple that true victory comes from personal excellence rather than others' defeat."}],"type":"paragraph"}
